HTML Lists Guide
1. Types of HTML Lists
Ordered List (<ol>)
Creates numbered lists
Uses <li> for list items
Example:

<ol>
    <li>First item</li>
    <li>Second item</li>
    <li>Third item</li>
</ol>

Attributes for <ol>:

type="" - Specifies the numbering type:
"1" - Numbers (default)
"A" - Uppercase letters
"a" - Lowercase letters
"I" - Uppercase Roman numerals
"i" - Lowercase Roman numerals
start="" - Specifies the starting number (e.g., start="5")
reversed - Reverses the order of numbers

Example with attributes:

Unordered List (<ul>)
Creates bulleted lists
Uses <li> for list items
Example:
<ul>
    <li>Coffee</li>
    <li>Tea</li>
    <li>Milk</li>
</ul>

ul {
    list-style-type: disc;    /* Default bullet */
    list-style-type: circle;  /* Circle bullet */
    list-style-type: square;  /* Square bullet */
    list-style-type: none;    /* No bullet */
}

Definition List (<dl>)
Creates a list of terms and descriptions
Uses <dt> for terms and <dd> for descriptions
Example:
<dl>
    <dt>HTML</dt>
    <dd>HyperText Markup Language - the standard markup language for web pages</dd>
    
    <dt>CSS</dt>
    <dd>Cascading Style Sheets - the language used to style HTML documents</dd>
</dl>

<ol>
    <li>First level
        <ul>
            <li>Nested bullet point</li>
            <li>Another nested point</li>
        </ul>
    </li>
    <li>Back to first level</li>
</ol>

Best Practices
Always close your list items (</li>)
Use semantic meaning:
<ol> for sequences
<ul> for unordered collections
<dl> for term definitions
Maintain proper indentation for nested lists
Use CSS for styling rather than deprecated HTML attributes
4. Common Use Cases
Navigation menus (<ul>)
Step-by-step instructions (<ol>)
Feature lists (<ul>)
FAQ sections (<dl>)
Site maps (<ul> with nested lists)